# The New York Times

# DEMOCRATS HELP JOHNSON SURVIVE BID TO OUST HIM

A ‘Catalystmic’ Crisis Lags in Race for Aid

# HORSE FORCES 360,000 TO Flee Homes

A ‘Catalystmic’ Crisis Lags in Race for Aid

# HORSE VOTES 359 TO 43

# By FRANCES ROBLES

Hundreds of thousands of people in Haiti are on the run from rampant gang violence and have abandoned their homes, a war-ridden humanitarian crisis that the United Nations describes as “catastrophic.”

Masses of homeless families flooding gang members who burned down their houses and killed their neighbors have taken over dozens of schools, churches and even government buildings. Many places have no running water, flushing toilets or garbage pickup.

The lacky ones are sleeping on a frozen slab.

“There are kids at my camp who have no parents,” said Angela Jesus, 16, who left her home up the Caribbean island of Dominica of Haiti’s capital, Port-au-Prince, in August at just 10 years old. “They don’t have a spot in their lives. They don’t have a place to sleep. They don’t have a place to eat. They don’t have a place to go.”

At least 360,000 people — more than half of the country’s population — are living in camps.

At least 360,000 people — more than half of the country’s population — are in camps.
